Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees and bring a #pot{} of water to the boil with
@salt{pinch}. Halve the @potato{2} and when the water is boiling, add to the pot
and cook for ~{10%minutes}. Then drain and pop on a #chopping board{}.

Place the flat edges of your potato on the board and make deep cuts into the
curved top of each potato half.

> Take care not to cut right through and careful not to burn yourself!

Arrange your potato in an #ovenproof dish{}, drizzle with a good glug of
@oil{drizzle}, a pinch of @salt{} and a grind of @black pepper{grind}. Shake your
dish to make sure they get a coating of everything! Pop on the top shelf of your
oven for ~{25-30%minutes} until crisp and brown.

While your potato is cooking, get on with the pork! Heat a drizzle of
@olive oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and fry the
@pork loin fillet{2} for ~{2-3%minutes} on each side, turning once, until each
piece is nicely browned.

> Don't wash your pan you'll need it later for the apple sauce!

Pop your pork on a #baking tray{}, generously grind over some
@black pepper{some} and cover with a sheet of #tinfoil{}. Cook for a further
~{12-15%minutes} on the middle shelf in your oven.

> The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Lift out, wrap loosely in tinfoil to rest and set aside until everything else is
ready.

> Resting the meat ensures it is lovely and juicy.

Meanwhile, put a #pot{} of water on to boil (you can use the same pot you used
to cook your potato!) and slice the @chantenay carrots{2} in half lengthways
(no need to peel!). Cook them in boiling water for ~{5-6%minutes}, until just
tender.

While your carrot is cooking, make your apple sauce. Quarter, peel and core the
@Cox's apple{2} and cut into 1cm thick slices, then add to the pan with your
cooked pork meat juices, the @honey{4}, @vegetable stock pot{1}, @apple and sage
jelly{2} and the @water{100}. Simmer for ~{5%minutes}, until your apple is soft.

When everything is ready, cut your pork into 1cm wide slices and serve with your
potato and carrots. Spoon your apple sauce over and enjoy.